messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Endpoints analysis

- Full HTTP request path: /users/{user}
  - Rationale: The routes/web.php file defines Route::resource('users', UserController::class)->only('show'); which creates the show route as GET /users/{user}. The {user} segment is a route parameter and will be bound to a User model (as seen by the method signature show(Request $request, User $user)).

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false
  - Rationale: Only the GET method is defined for the show action via the resource route. No other methods (POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS, TRACE) are defined for this endpoint.

- HEAD acceptable: true
  - Rationale: The endpoint is a GET route. In Laravel, HEAD requests are typically handled automatically for GET routes by the framework, even though HEAD is not explicitly defined in the code. This is a framework behavior, not an explicit route declaration.

- POST acceptable: false
- OPTIONS acceptable: false
- TRACE acceptable: false
- GET acceptable: true
- PUT acceptable: false
- DELETE acceptable: false
- PATCH acceptable: false

Explanation

- The UserController@show endpoint is created by a Laravel resource route for users with only the show action, so it responds to GET /users/{user}.
- The path parameter {user} corresponds to a route parameter that Laravel will use for route model binding to a User instance (as indicated by the show method accepting User $user and the web.php route definition).
- HEAD is not explicitly declared, but Laravel automatically handles HEAD requests for existing GET routes, so HEAD is considered acceptable based on the frameworkâ€™s behavior.
- All other HTTP methods are not defined for this route, so they are not acceptable for this endpoint.
